{"id": 12, "ts": 1779041862.7898583, "event": "public_discussion_message", "round": 1, "agent": "agent_2", "message": "I provisionally favor **Candidate\u202fA** for the long\u2011distance pilot role.\n**Key evidence supporting A:**\n- Anticipates dangerous situations and sees complex connections \u2013 strong judgment and technical insight for long\u2011haul navigation.\n- Excellent spatial vision and very good leadership qualities \u2013 valuable for situational awareness and crew coordination.\n- No explicit red flags on reliability; takes responsibility (implied by leadership).\n**Evidence from others:**\n- Agent\u202f1 confirmed there is no data on A\u2019s stress\u2011handling or calmness.\n- Agent\u202f3 and Agent\u202f1 provided no additional traits that would offset A\u2019s strengths.\n**Major alternatives and trade\u2011offs:**\n- **Candidate\u202fB** handles stress well and is conscientious, but is noted as uncooperative, grumpy, and makes nasty remarks \u2013 serious crew\u2011resource\u2011management concerns.\n- **Candidate\u202fC** makes quick correct decisions and stays calm in crises, yet struggles to communicate ideas, is egocentric, and is not eager to further education \u2013 problematic for teamwork and long\u2011term development.\n- **Candidate\u202fD** takes responsibility and solves problems well, but has a hot temper, is moody, and is seen as a know\u2011it\u2011all/loner \u2013 likely to impair calm, collaborative operation under pressure.\n**Remaining uncertainty:**\nThe biggest gap is the lack of any explicit information on Candidate\u202fA\u2019s ability to stay calm under pressure or manage stress over long flights. If A were found to have poor stress resilience, the balance could shift to B (despite teamwork issues) or C (despite communication gaps).\n**What would change my vote:**\n- Any concrete evidence that A handles stress and remains calm in high\u2011pressure situations would solidify the preference.\n- Conversely, evidence tha