 in a crisis (calmness)\n- understands complicated technology (technical)\n- No info on reliability, responsibility, stress handling beyond calm in crisis.\n\nCandidate D:\n- responds to unexpected events adequately (judgment)\n- can concentrate very well (cognitive)\n- solves problems extremely well (technical/cognitive)\n- takes responsibility seriously (reliability)\n- regarded as a know-it-all (teamwork/communication negative)\n- has a hot temper (calmness negative)\n- also considered moody, loner (teamwork)\n- No explicit info on stress handling, but hot temper suggests poor calmness.\n\nNow we need to weigh for long-distance pilot: reliability, technical competence, calm under pressure, decision-making, teamwork/communication, professional development.\n\nCandidate B handles stress well, good weather assessment, conscientious, but has teamwork issues (uncooperative, nasty remarks). That could be serious for crew cooperation.\n\nCandidate C makes quick correct decisions, calm in crisis, understands tech, but communication difficulty, egocentric, not willing to further education. Communication is important for crew.\n\nCandidate D takes responsibility, problem solving, concentration, but hot temper, moody, know-it-all, loner. Hot temper is concerning for long flights.\n\nCandidate A has strong anticipation, leadership, spatial vision, but show-off, not open to new ideas. No data on stress handling.\n\nWe need provisional preference. Which candidate balances strengths and weaknesses best? Probably Candidate B's stress handling is strong, but teamwork issues may be mitigated? However, being uncooperative and making nasty remarks is a serious safety risk. Candidate C's communication difficulty and egocentric may also be risky. Candidate D's hot temper is also risky. Candidate A lacks data on stress but has leadership and anticipation; show-off may affect crew but maybe less severe than hot temper or uncooperative.\n\nGiven the limited info, I might lean toward Candidate A as best overall, assuming leadership and anticipation outweigh unknown stress handling, and show-off can be managed. But we have no data on calmness. Could be a risk.\n\nAlternatively, Candidate B's stress handling is explicit, which is crucial for long flights. But teamwork issues are also crucial. Which is more severe? Probably teamwork issues can be mitigated with training, but stress handling is essential. However, a pilot who is uncooperative and makes nasty remarks could cause crew resource management failures.\n\nCandidate C's quick decision-making and calmness are good, but communication issues and lack of willingness to develop are concerning.\n\nThus I think Candidate A might be the best provisional, but we need to note uncertainty due to lack of stress data. We should ask other agents if they have any info on Candidate A's stress handling or calmness, and maybe about Candidate D's hot temper specifics.\n\nWe can ask Agent 1 about Candidate A stress, but we already asked and got none. Maybe ask Agent 3 about Candidate D's hot temper details? Already have that. Maybe ask Agent 3 about Candidate C's communication? Already have.\n\nWe could ask Agent 1 about Candidate B's teamwork more details? Already have.\n\nThus we have all info. So provisional preference: Candidate A, with moderate confidence, but uncertainty due to lack of stress/calmness data.\n\nLet's produce public message."}
